In Nicaragua, defendants are not usually obligated to post bail pending a legal proceeding, even if they are facing severe accusations. After 90 days, women can only gain an abortion if they face health risks or their fetus or pregnancy are already damaged. The doctors and hospitals legally required to provide abortions in cases of rape, incest, or inviable fetus, are proposed to be kept very silent about the (the legal) procedure.

What is needed

In order to shift power to women and grow it, Nicaragua is in need of a true shift in mindset, alongside a shift in resources and rights. A true shift away from culturally-sponsored sexism is needed, in order for the women working in Nicaragua to quit suffering at a relentless rate. Legal support needs to be supported in the form of a center for women, and it is also needed in order for women to have a safe place to discuss politics. For government to listen to the wants and needs of its people, there needs to be a serious and far-reaching change in politics. A change of mindset is needed, as well as one of access to resources, and one of women's rights. Women in Nicaragua need to have access to education, birth control, family paid leave, and a lot more.
